\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Full name. Henry James Thomas Russell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}418 Uttoxeter Road{\*\xmlclose}, 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 You are married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Your year of marriage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 1929.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 And your year of birth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 September 1900. September the eight, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 And your birthplace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Oh derby. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Well we - if you don\rquote 
t want me to - when I - my mother married in the 1890 period and I was born in 1900 in Mansfield Street which has now been modernized, new housing fl
ats and all that, in a pub, me grandfather had taken a pub over. My grandfather had been one of Haslams, you know the Haslams people of Derby who made the - overseas - freezing system and all that \lquote 
tkl the Australians and New Zealand began to bring the meat back, and they formed this - this firm of Haslams again there in Chester Green, Mansfield Road, Dervy, father}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556407\charrsid15021746 \rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid556407\charrsid15021746 as}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746  one of - me grandfather was one of Haslams first eight men, in the 1850
\rquote s - early 50 - \rquote 40 period and - member of his union of that day, iron founders and all the rest of it you know, anyway we had a bit of trouble, a strike in the 18 - about the mid 1890\rquote 
s and - he was getting on a bit then and - and the pub was gong and he took it. It was only a beer house, quite a nice place, not long sinc
e it was pulled down, it became redundant about twenty years ago as a public house. I was born there and it got to the stage where it was hard work, me mother was doing this work, I was the only one I - the family then, I should be five when we left the p
ub and went to live in a - a newer house, terrace type house at the other end of Mansfield Road, Chester Green again. And we stayed there until I was married.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 You went to live in this newer place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 What year would that be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 In 1905.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Did you make any other moves up to the end of 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 I had three other brothers and two sisters. Yes. Six of us altogether.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Can you tell me the birth order and spacing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Yes. Three boys firs, my brother John Wilfred, 1908. Yes. The next brother, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid11022487\charrsid15021746 Charles}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746  William, April 1910.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 You were the eldest then were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 You were the eldest in 1900?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 That\rquote s right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Then the next two came 1908 and 1910?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 1910, yes. Then a brother Stanley, he came late - November 1911. Two fairly quick then. Then the first sister was born in 1915. 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Nancy{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. And the second, Elsie, was born in 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 My mother was twenty-two and my father was twenty-four. That\rquote s right. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Oh he was born in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. His - his father came from {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname country-region}}Scotland{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} when the firm he worked with came down this part and set up a foundry in - in 
{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}, that was Russells foundry in which they }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11022487\charrsid15021746 produced}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746  some of the early heating system, gas stoves and that kind of thing you see. My father was a skilled fitter, did his seven years apprenticeship and so on. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Can you tell me a bit more about the sort of job he did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 
Well it was - fire grates and that kind of thing and then later on the stove, the gas stoves and that kind of - of system. He was a member of his union called the Heating and Domestic Engineers, Whitesmiths and General Iron Workers, and he was Secretary 
of that branch in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Derby{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
 for forty years. But in 1910 he was victimized by the firm to which he was related, only as a - a - his - his father - his father was a cousin of the people who started the firm, because he\rquote d dared to go and ask for a little bit of 
an increase as the union Secretary - branch Secretary, for the men on the job and - well, they turfed him out and so an and he was unemployed for a number - many months actually. That was in 1910 - 1910. I was at school then. And I used to - he was - he w
as too - he used to get - he got ten shillings a week from his union, victimization pay, no other income, he could have gone to the Poor Law and applied, but again he was too proud to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Did they actually call it victimization pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Yes. The union did, yes. And the union paid him ten shillings a week you see. Well that\rquote 
s all they had to live on, the rent was about five and six in those days and - me grandfather was still }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11022487\charrsid15021746 living}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 
 with us and he was getting a small - superannuation from his union, the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid11022487\charrsid15021746 Iron founders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 
, about six or - five or six shillings a week, and they had to manage. Of course I was - there was only two of us in the family then, me and the next brother. And - me dad was too proud to go to - to what was then called the old Poor Law,
 assistance, they used to call it that, apply for anything and - he took a job on for a - a week or so, delivering leaflets advertising domestic soaps or something like that and I - during the school holidays in August and I went round with him and we wal
ked miles round Derby delivering these things, we only got - probably - I don\rquote 
t know how much he got, perhaps - ten shillings a week for doing it, perhaps two shillings a day - half a crown a day, something like that. And finally he got a job in another iro
n foundry people in derby - after being out of work from, I should say, a number of months anyway. Of course there was no unemployment pay in that day, it was Poor Law you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 So he got another job then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Still in his own trade?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4794022 HR  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Similar yes. That\rquote s right. That\rquote s right.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5077811 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5065330\charrsid15021746 Did he stay in that job all his life?
